  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is that feeling of anxiety when someone’s identity—like being female or a person of color—makes them worry they’ll perform worse because of negative stereotypes about their group. For me, as a transgender mechanic in Philadelphia, I’ve seen it firsthand. When I’m working on cars, especially with younger kids or people who don’t understand, they might say things like, 'You’re not supposed to know how to fix this,' or 'Girls don’t do mechanics.' That’s not just mean—it’s a real stressor. I’ve never had formal education, but I learned through hands-on work and my parents’ stories. They taught me to fix things without the fancy jargon, which is how I became a mechanic. So, yes, we should address stereotype threat in STEM. It’s not about fixing people—it’s about changing the environment so everyone feels safe to try. For example, in my shop, I make sure to have clear, friendly conversations with everyone, especially kids who might feel left out. We do simple workshops where they can touch tools and see that fixing cars is for anyone, not just a specific group. It’s important to talk about it openly, not in a lecture way, but in a way that feels personal and real. My high neuroticism means I’m sensitive to stress, so I’ve learned to be patient with others who might feel the same way. In the end, it’s not about changing the rules of STEM—it’s about making sure no one feels like they can’t belong there.",
